{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488379"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:39:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:39:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"425"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/425"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.85,0.04,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"425"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114578"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/425"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"425"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96579"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"182"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31524"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31525"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42083"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114578"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man is retrieved from the scene of a motor vehicle crash, in which he sustained a head injury. He is unconscious and endotracheal intubation is performed. A CT scan of his head is performed and shows intracranial haemorrhage. He is on warfarin for a prosthetic mitral valve. His INR is 2.5.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to giving vitamin K, which one of the following is the most appropriate management of his coagulation status?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cryoprecipitate","Prothrombin complex concentrate and fresh frozen plasma","Platelet transfusion","Idarucizumab","Activated charcoal and tranexamic acid"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, a warfarinised patient has presented with a life-threatening intracranial haemorrhage. Warfarin reversal is performed according to \u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2013/198/4/update-consensus-guidelines-warfarin-reversal\u0022\u003Eestablished guidelines\u003C/a\u003E from the Australasian Society of Thrombosis and Haemostasis, which advocate the urgent administration of intravenous vitamin K, \u003Cstrong\u003Eprothrombin complex concentrate (\u003C/strong\u003EPCC\u003Cstrong\u003E; \u003C/strong\u003Etrade name\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003EBeriplex\u00ae\u003Cstrong\u003E), and fresh frozen plasma\u003C/strong\u003E (FFP) for life-threatening or critical organ bleeding in patients on warfarin regardless of INR.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWarfarin is a vitamin K epoxide reductase inhibitor that depletes the circulating levels of clotting factors II, VII, IX, and X. The generally available formulation of PCC in Australia (Beriplex\u00ae) contains factors II, IX, and X and therefore guidelines recommend also giving FFP (which contains all clotting factors) to supplement factor VII. PCC and FFP can normalise the INR within 15 minutes, but these exogenous factors will also become depleted while warfarin continues to circulate and inhibit the formation of new endogenous factors; therefore, vitamin K also must be given to achieve a sustained effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegarding the other options presented:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIdarucizumab is a reversal agent for dabigatran\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECryoprecipitate contains factors VIII and XIII, von Willebrand factor, fibrinogen, and fibronectin; it is used in cases of critical bleeding with low fibrinogen levels\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet transfusion may be considered in emergencies to counteract antiplatelet medications (e.g. prior to emergency surgery)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActivated charcoal (within 2 hours of most recent dose) and tranexamic acid are sometimes used where bleeding occurs on a NOAC without an available reversal agent\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Warfarin reversal in the setting of life-threatening bleeding should include urgent vitamin K, prothrombin complex concentrate, and fresh frozen plasma"],"references":["An update of consensus guidelines for warfarin reversal. Tran et al; Australasian Society of Thrombosis and Haemostasis (ASTH). Med J Aust. 2013 Mar 4;198(4):198-9.","Management of Patients on Non-Vitamin K Antagonist Oral Anticoagulants in the Acute Care and Periprocedural Setting: A Scientific Statement From the American Heart Association. Raval et al. Circulation. 2017 Mar 7;135(10):e604-e633."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96579"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"425"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96579"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T16:59:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T16:59:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"425"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114578"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type